{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti (Chapter 1, section 1.6 \"The Document\")** warns against forged copies of documents using this simile: \"Just as a reflection in a mirror, though unreal, appears as real, so skilled persons make copies of documents.\"[^1]\n\nThe nearly identical warning also appears in **Kātyāyana Smṛti (Chapter 26 \"The Examination of Documents\")**: \"Just as an image in a mirror, though unreal, appears real, so do skillful people create copies of documents.\"[^2]\n\nBoth are classical Sanskrit legal treatises (Smṛtis) on judicial procedure, addressing document forgery in their respective sections on written instruments (e.g., deeds of debt, sale, partition).\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c67c7e).\n\n[^2]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, *Chapter 26*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/26/translation/#p-ffea01).",
